==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Side-chain theory
<hw>Side"-chain` the`o*ry</hw>. <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A
theory proposed by <person>P. Ehrlich</person> as a chemical explanation
of immunity phenomena. In brief outline it is as follows: Animal cells
and bacteria are complex aggregations of molecules, which are themselves
complex. Complex molecules react with one another through certain of
their side chains, but only when these side chains have a definite
correspondence in structure (this accounts for the specific action of
antitoxins).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sided</ent>⟦br⟧
